76561197963161776,Recommended,248860,20409083,"Posted: 8 January, 2016",all,Razor,"Note: I bought and played mostly on the GOG version of the game, hence why I have less than 2 hours in Steam. I probably logged over 100 hours.Anyways...What this game does right is giving you lots of options when it comes to survival. Too often survival games feel limited, like things you should be able to do easily in a real life situation just aren't available in game. A couple examples that come to mind:- Need to boil something but don't have a cooking pot? Use a tin can!- Need to make fire but don't have a lighter? Rub two sticks together or use sunlight and a piece of glass!- Need a container to carry items but don't have a backpack? Use a plastic shopping bag!- Need bandages? Rip clothes, get rags. Need clean bandages? Boil rags.- Need string? Rip rags.Nice features include:- 'Building' your camp: pick an abandoned building with the appliances you need, place traps, leave a sleeping bag... Not a whole lot of options but you do feel like you have your own personal secure spot you can come back to.- An engaging storyline that makes you want to find out about what happened to the world and yourself. An interesting lore as well.- Lots of crafting options to get the stuff you need to survive.- Skills that give you special abilities- Pretty good learning curve: you'll have to keep trying at first until you learn the basics. Then you'll manage to survive fairly well, and you'll still have many more things to learn and discover. There's lots of stuff you'll have to figure out on your own (or you can use the wiki).- Overall, enough content to keep you engaged for many hours.- Low hardware requirements. Will probably run on that $200 laptop you bought to take notes in class (check the specs to be sure though).Cons:- The game is text-based with a graphical interface. Nothing is animated, few things are drawn, most is just described through text. The combat system especially takes some getting used too as well. It's very playable and some people like that style, but for some people it's a deal-breaker. So be warned.- Only one save/permadeath (although you can easily circumvent that).- Not being able to pick all skills can make the game feel limited, forcing you to play again to explore other things (you can mod the game to get all skills though).- The randomness can be harsh sometimes and force you to restart many times before you'll get lucky, have a good start and actually get somewhere.- Many random encounters don't have a ""good"" resolution to them, sometimes making you feel like the game just ties your hands excessively and won't let you try hard enough, or making you feel like your skills are useless. Some encounters can actually punish you severely, with no way for you to predict that your decisions will lead to a really bad outcome. This is in deep contrast with the rest of the game where you have so many options to accomplish what you want to do.Overall I recommend it to people who enjoy the survival genre, have the patience to fail, learn and try again repeatedly, and who can overlook the game sometimes throwing you in tough situations without you being able to do anything about it. People who aren't so hardcore can just mod the game a bit to make it easier and can circumvent the one save/permadeath feature."
