76561198089899444,Recommended,248860,28905428,Posted: 1 January,all,Osric,"What a cracking little gem this game is. Brutal and unforgiving though it is is does manage that rarest of feats in providing an emergent story. The moment you get cocky you're toast. Complaints against the RNG element are not without basis, but then survival is like that. I'm not a massive rogue-like fan and would usually prefer the ability to save, but I realised this game had something special when I died after a 6 hour solid playthrough and smiled rather than rage-quit. The graphics are abysmal, the menus somewhat clunky and I come from an era that had to live through low res graphics and don't find them charming and rretro. But never has a game drawn so heavily on the imagination, and never have I experienced a game that manages to bring a crappy low res hex to life.The combat is what sets it apart from Project Zomboid, apart from the deep joy of not having to deal with ***king zombies. Whilst somewhat barebones it does make you very careful about how you go about it. In addition there doesn't come a time when easy mobs are trivial bore to swat away. That feral dog can still trouble an unfortunate or over-confident veteran. Every encounter has the potential to send you into a downward spiral if not handled with care.The luck cuts both ways, I had a very fortunate shot with a sling that set me up nicely with very useful loot, which I lost because I thought it made me king of the hill.In short if you really want a zombie free realistic survival experience and you have the imagination to paint the picture in your mind rather than have it rendered in technicolor for yo,u then this game is a must buy. The dev deserves high praise for this little cracker and whilst it is by no means perfect and regularly kicks you in the nads there's something special about this one that spectacularly succeeds in  being greater than the sum of its parts."
