76561198021030392,Not Recommended,248860,19541115,"Posted: 6 December, 2015",all,Polar,"I've played this game for 14 hours, and I'm angry. Hear me roar.I played for 14 hours, slaughtered COUNTLESS beasties, raiders and robbers. I killed something called a ""melonhead"" and I've slaughtered so many dogs I could wear their skins and pretend to be the wolf-man.It was at that time - as I munched down another human steak, made on the desecrated remains of a man who had tried to steal my sled in the middle of the night, that I was assaulted. Well, it was actually while I slept after having eaten the corpse of the aformentioned adversary, seeing as time apparently stops when you eat things.In any case, let me recount to you, the story of Philip the Doghide boy.Philip, just as any man, awoke from cryogenic stasis in a secret lab, where he was quickly faced with a hideous creature screaming like the midnight wind 'cross a praire of bones so sharp as knives. And much like that praire of bones, the dogman was soon still and dead. You see, Philip was a total badass, and he vanquished this horrific beast with a few swift uppercuts and rock-hard right-left combos. The beast lay dead, and not satisfied with merely having sent this beast's soul to dogman-heaven, Philip decided that it's skin looked comfortable. He grabbed a shard of glass, cut it open and wore it's pelt - face and all, possibly while dancing to some trance-music and smearing cheap lipstick on himself. Naked. In front of a mirror.After that psychadellic trip, Philip wandered out into the wilderness, wearing nothing but the skin of his dead adversary. He was messed with. Attacked by rabid dogs and feral.. Dogs. And more dogs. This game has a lot of dogs. If you don't like killing dogs, this is probably not the game for you.Anyway, needless to say, dogs never really posed a problem for Philip. Philip had two good pairs of hands, and he had a shank made of glass in one of them. Philip was not to be ♥♥♥♥ed with.Now, Philip was a hulking mass of death, even when armed with nothing but a shard of glass, so I'll assume you understand what happened when Philip found a crowbar and a loaded shotgun in a shed. That's right. Philip turned into a lean, mean, psychopathic killing machine. This brings us to a dark chapter of Philip's life. The killing. The killing never stopped.Philip was a soulless husk of a man, and that crowbar whispered sweet things in his ears at night. It craved for blood. Lusted for it. Philip was renamed ""Philip Mordake"".Philip tried to fight it, of course. Philip was no murderer.. Philip merely loved to kill dogs, but that didn't matter. For each person that crossed Philip's path, the crowbar screamed. It pleaded, begged and demanded of Philip.. Terrible things. Great things. But terrible things.It drove him to insanity, the whispering. The screams. They all melded together as Philip gave in to the crowbar's crazed yelling. He'd separate flesh from bone, and smash until there was nothing left but something that barely resembeled a human. He'd eat the flesh. Why not? Cut it loose with a shard of glass, and eat chunk by chunk until he was no longer starving.Philip's path on this strange earth was carved from the blood and bone of any that entered his path. Any that dared touch his sled. Philip was a cruel God on this earth, his fury tempestous and his retribution violent and brutal as it was swift. He cut many a foe from existance, and wore their remains as trophies.This brings us to the end of Philip's journey. For Philip had been surprised to wake up in the middle of the night, at the sound of somebody stealing his sled! That could not happen - no not at all. And Philip's recourse to this - though predictable - was a thing to behold. He knocked down that poor thief, and whaled with his crowbar until there was naught left of his adversary. Philip hadn't even been injured at this. He was in perfect health, and continued to be so as he smeared himself with the blood of his enemy (note; you can't actually do this in the game. You'll wish you could, though.) and sat himself down again. He dozed off, and once more awoke. This time, to the face of the very first foe that he'd faced.It was a Dogman, looming above him like a gaunt, shadowy behemoth. The crowbar awoke. It screamed. It begged for blood, and Philip didn't have to be asked twice. He leapt for the creature! He cut it down, and bit it's flesh with that accursed crowbar time and time again! A hailstorm of blows weakened the beast, and it desperately slashed out!...Philip was struck in the heart, and died immediately. And the crowbar fell from his hand, going silent.. It was just a normal crowbar.Now, you might think that's an amusing story. Or maybe you hated that story, but let me tell you what.I spent 14 HOURS. 14 BLOODY HOURS ON PHILIP.Philip was a GODDAMNED MONSTER! He was the toughest thing since diamonds armed with shanks in a cuban jail.He'd survived battles with up to three opponents at once, and though injured, he'd come out on top.And now he just got killed instantly because of some fantastic stroke of good fortune for some psuedo-werewolf.This game is interesting, but it's interesting for about 10 minutes. If you've discovered amazing loot in one house, you've basically found all there is in this game. Sure, there are random events and such, but very few of them actually lead anywhere. You're Philip, and you'll always be Philip. Not Philippa, or Sam, or James the Jive♥♥♥♥♥Jukebox Jockey. Philip.You'll pick your perks, disadvantages and roll out. You die because of silly reasons or because you had a bad start. And then you have to start all over, without any progress having been made.After a while, it becomes tedious. It's not fun to micro-manage your campfire, clothes, hydration and hunger-levels, as well as spend the ENTIRE GAME TRYING TO FALL ASLEEP, I MEAN♥♥♥♥♥♥ JUST FALL ASLEEP, MAN! YOU JUST MASSACRED AN ENTIRE VILLAGE!All in all, I'd refund this game if I hadn't hate♥♥♥♥ed 14 hours of gameplay out of it. Do yourself a favour and look at a youtube-clip of somebody playing it without audio first. That will be your life in this game. Like what you see? Go for it."
76561198037427689,Not Recommended,248860,34161225,Posted: 10 August,all,RobotDeathParty,"I'm a bit disappointed with this game because my issue, as many have already pointed out in longer and more detailed reviews, is entirely with the first-impression a game like this gives. I had actually followed this game for a while and finally got to play it today. I played for about an hour straight and my whole experience was the following : Make character, explore surrounding hexes of beginning campsite area, fail to find any items for 90% of scavenging explored hexes, attract unwanted attention indefinitely, proceed to either get mauled by feral dogs or have to surrender to some random jackass that, from what I understand, removes *at least* one item(including containers which actually takes the container plus all items inside it counting it as a single item) from your inventory(which, to add insult to injury, meant I lost my starting gown and was literally naked - no items at all). Rinse and repeat. No fun at all.In fact, it's all because of RNG and the issue is the chance of success when performing actions. You start the game with essentially nothing. Following the first-time tutorial messages, you'll always scavenge the starting area to get a gown and, seemingly useless, shards of glass. Virtually every single start had me next to a small town with storage sheds and abandoned houses/mobile homes but the loot chance bar is at ~5% without any items to help you scavenge. The stealth bar was usually at around ~50% or ~75% without the hiding skill but was still constantly alerting enemies to my location(which then proceeded with me dying). Using the hiding skill reduces loot chance but increases stealth chance(even though I did alert enemies to position using the skill with it increasing it to ~90%). See the issue? Either stick with a very very low chance to get indefinitely useless loot in a spot I kept on spawning next to and alert enemies OR lower that alert chance but get no loot at all. I had *one* single ""lucky"" run in the 1 hour I played and it involved me getting a crowbar, which increases loot chance but lowers stealth. Well, guess, what, completely useless for me in that run because the areas I scavenged with the crowbar consistently resulted in injuries, no loot, and alerting various enemies, which is what ended that run because I quickly got beaten down by 3 dogs. This experience was the whole the 1-hour in, what, 10 runs?It's not even like I'm bad at these types of games. I could do literally nothing about the starting of each run since gathering loot is initially very low, entirely run by RNG, and you start with nothing while also having odds of getting loot against you tenfold. I didn't even understand most of the menus because without certain starting-perks, certain stats are hidden against you(which I assume this includes combat too because I didn't see any combat stats like hit chance or item stats such as weapon damage, range, etc.).To cut a long story short, it was a disappointing experience because it's yet another game(a rogue-like, too) that depends almost entirely on RNG while giving you no long-term benefits beyond death, meaning you're almost entirely playing against luck itself(and everyone already knows RNG/random number generator mechanics are ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t. See : Darkest Dungeon) sort of like a gambling game where it's a win-lose 50-50 respectively. You go as far as you want risking it every single instance(e.g. every draw of a card or every individual action in this game), except in this game you get literally nothing if you die.I would've like it more if it didn't come off as so threatening and hardcore because, yes, a lot of roguelikes suffer from this issue. I still haven't gotten much out of FTL for exact reason, because the game starts off as very overwhelming and hardcore, and I got scared off by it. Same thing happened here.Also, as a random aside since it doesn't fit into any of my ranting... Aside from the first couple tutorial messages, the game explained *nothing*. Even crafting was just weird, especially since the game presumably has crafting recipes that you have to find via scavenging. Oh boy... fun.If anyone disagrees then I *dare* you to try and create a starting-the-game guide that doesn't essentially tell someone how to play the game, because if you can't then my thoughts will be pointed towards how linear the game would be in the end in terms of progression."
