76561198110012916,Not Recommended,248860,12043887,"Posted: 10 September, 2014",all,grimrist,"There crux of this game is you wandering around the wilderness re-arraning your pack to carry the maximum amount of junk you find. Descriptive working  titles include:""Homeless Man Shopping Cart Arrranger""or ""Vagrant Cardboard Box Simulator""also ""Hobo with a Shotgun Plastic Bag Minmaxxer.""The idea for this this game and it's mechanic is very ingenious. The developer is very dedicated.The RNG element makes the skill cieling very low.In general: Random elements exist postively in a game for two primary funtions; to create variety & to approximate the large & infinte variables of reality. While I appreciate their intended role in this game is to do precisely those two things the simple fact is their implementation is coutner-productive here.The simple fact is if the RNG doesn't grant you the ability to find clothes in the first 12 tiles or so your game is over. God help you should you get attacked before findin a weapon.I really liked this game (& the developer) but I can;t in good faith reccomend it.Also the combat is like doing the Math portion of the SATs whilst ȿhit-faced; an ardous ordeal whereupon your efforts to apply skill or reasoning only inhibit the actual deciding factor: random chance."
76561197996972957,Not Recommended,248860,32374252,Posted: 12 June,all,sir Evans,"TL:DR;I cannot recommend it due to few fatal flaws.This is a flash game of armorgames quality, sale material not worth more than 6$.Worse it is aimed only at a certain group of people with masochistic tendencies. Read on to find why.Review:NEO Scavenger, an odd name for a title that claims to be post-apocalyptic survival game.It hardly achieves what it promises and unfortunately uses few tricks to hide its flaws from the player for the first few hours.Graphics: 5/10No excuses for uninspired graphics. Sure, it's not the most important part of the game, but the choice of tiles, buildings, etc. is waaaaaaaay to poor.Sounds: 8/10Actually pretty good. Keeps atmosphere. Ambient, dark elements accompany the game pretty good.Gameplay: 5/10Well... good for the first few hours.Rogue-like random map and loot, random encounters etc.The problem is that it is yet another game which uses brutal RNG and player's death as an excuse for lack of any in depth mechanics and content.Once you get a grasp of this title, you will realise that there is nothing to aim at, except for maybe very difficult base infiltration mission which is also an end game.You see, this game has totally nothing to offer.- no skill progression- no character progression- no camp building- no real crafting- no loot variety- no enemies variety- no real missions and NPCs- no factions you can actually join in a meaningful way- not possible to start a gang of friendly NPCs and roam the landThere is simply nothing in terms of gameplay that after few initial deaths can hold you to this title.It's all the same - walk around, kill mobs, loot corpses, scavenge, return to camp (now probably ransacked by NPCs.Fetch wood, boil water, cook meat, repeat till you die of diarrhea or other plagues.You can't, for example, raid some bunker or a military base and bar the entrance from the inside, thus being shielded from harm. You can't really upgrade it (there is room 17 in starting location, but I got a bug and it vanished, taking all the stuff with it). You can't start a farm or hydroponics at the camp. Can't make bullets.With crafting limited as it is, with no solar panels to recharge all those laptops and batteries and stuff, you are either forced to buy technology from remaining megacity or live like a tribal.Only you can't have a tribe because you cannot befriend any of the numberless horde of nameless NPCs.Therefore this game is only recommended either on sale or to a group of people who enjoy dying and starting over against whatever devilry RNG has conjured against a player this time."
